{"id":"1410.6378","submitter":"Matteo Giordano","authors":"Matteo Giordano, Tamas G. Kovacs (Debrecen, Inst. Nucl. Res.), Ferenc\n  Pittler (Eotvos U.)","title":"Understanding localisation in QCD through an Ising-Anderson model","comments":"7 pages, 3 figures. Contribution to the proceedings of the 32nd\n  International Symposium on Lattice Field Theory (Lattice 2014), 23-28 June\n  2014, Columbia University, New York, NY, USA","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-lat","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Above the QCD chiral crossover temperature, the low-lying eigenmodes of the\nDirac operator are localised, while moving up in the spectrum states become\nextended. This localisation/delocalisation transition has been shown to be a\ngenuine second-order phase transition, in the same universality class as that\nof the 3D Anderson model. The existence of localised modes and the effective\ndimensional reduction can be tentatively explained as a consequence of local\nfluctuations of the Polyakov loop, that provide 3D on-site disorder, in analogy\nto the on-site disorder of the Anderson model. To test the viability of this\nexplanation we study a 3D effective, Anderson-like model, with on-site disorder\nprovided by the spins of a spin model, which mimics the Polyakov loop dynamics.\nOur preliminary results show that localised modes are present in the ordered\nphase, thus supporting the proposed mechanism for localisation in QCD.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 23 Oct 2014 14:44:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-10-24"}
